Fable is a game that came to my mind as well while playing this game. ESPECIALLY that fantasy illusion world you go to in the Blood and Wine DLC. Pulled be right back to that game.Red Dead Redemption also shares a surprisingly wide set of features, from an art direction standpoint, the horse mechanics and auto-following of roads and NPCs, to wild-life and sidequests, and a hint of nagging domestic issues for the main character.Skyrim has just become this huge household name that gets thrown around in comparisons and criticisms. The legend of the game has clouded what it actually is. It's a game that nailed exploration unlike any other before it, but when broken down to its individual parts, is pretty lackluster and hasn't aged super well. While there's some great lessons to take from it, I don't think it should be used as a blueprint for all future open world type games, but you'll find almost any Youtube comment section would disagree with me there.

I think the issue isn't that she perse made a false statement. I wouldn't even say it was the fact that she didn't correct it. Because lets be honest, lots of times things are printed, and the author didn't find all the details or know them. That would be a dangerous precedent. However what it really is about is this. Journalist puts forth a statement that is false about another personPublic call it out as false/is common knowledge as being false(not as great a defense)journalist links to a source they recognize as being reliable that their statement is truesource then explicitly replies in an official statement saying journalist is wrongAccused person and public again demand that the statement be amendedjournalist again refusesaccused services lawsuit against journalistseems pretty cut and dry to me honestly. If other people help you to understand that what you said was factually incorrect, then your responsibility as a journalist is to ammend what you said. Anything short of that is slander/liable whatever the one is for writing. After this point you clearly have a case that the journalist has an agenda to attempt to cause harm to the reputation of the accused, showing extreme bias against them. This was not some random joe on the street, this is a person whose responsibility is to tell the public about current events, and this is just stirring up hate against the accused for no good reason. How hard is it to say \whoops

Charlie, you do have some misinformation in here. You're thinking of a .50cal BMG rifle round, which can definitely go through vehicles and many building materials, but the weapon used was a Desert Eagle, and the .50cal designation refers to the bullet being half an inch in diameter. The Desert Eagle .50 AE ammunition has less than an eighth of the black powder behind it as a BMG rifle round has. It will still kill a bear but it doesn't have nearly the penetrative power of a BMG rifle round, so two car doors will stop it (one will not, and certainly a phone book won't). Also, it's readily available from Cheaper than Dirt and other online retailers.
